<HEADLINE>
Radcliffe, Grint and Watson
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<POST>
<POSTER> Tweedle Dee &lt;kva...@ku.edu&gt; </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-11-25T21:36:00 </POSTDATE>
I've just been rewatching all the HP movies. Here's an assessment of
the trio:

(i) Radcliffe: Began a little shakily with PS, but has grown in
stature and confidence since then. I like his sense of calm, and he
has a certain reserve in his acting. That suits his character well -
because Harry Potter is a natural leader, and a good leader has to
have a higher level of maturity than those he leads and the ability to
remain calm in the face of adversity. Radcliffe gives the character of
Harry that sense of poise.

(ii) Grint: I thought Grint was okay in PS, but then, his performance
took a nosedive in CoS - he just mugged his way all through the movie.
That was a one note performance that got old really quick for me. He
has improved since then, however, and he was okay in PoA and gave a
pretty good account of himself in GoF. I think the Ron of the books is
a little more tentative than the Ron of GoF and especially OoTP, but
this may well be due to screenplay and screen time limitations for the
character. The character of Ron is an especially challenging one - he
is not as heroic as Harry, but he is not a wimp either. He is in a
grey zone where he is meek and timid, and incapable of standing up to
Harry the way Hermione can, and also has a strong inferiority
complex,  while at the same time being fiercely loyal and capable of
putting his life on the line for his friends, as he does on several
occasions all through the series. It's not easy to play such a
character and show all his shades - and perhaps it would be harsh to
blame Grint for the slight disappointment I feel at the way Ron has
been portrayed and played so far in the series.

(iii) Watson: This is the one role that I have real issues with. I
think both Radcliffe and Grint were a little slow off the blocks, but
have grown into their roles as the series has progressed. Emma Watson,
on the other hand, has gone the other way. I thought she nailed the
character of Hermione in PS and CoS - she was perky, a little bossy
and had a certain know-it-all eagerness about her which was fun to
watch and which added a lot to all of her scenes with Radcliffe and
Grint. But something has happened to her since then. She has looked
too ... high strung in the subsequent movies. Whenever I saw her on
screen in the OoTP, for instance, I felt like injecting a dose of
sedative into her to get her to breathe and relax a little bit. Take
the post-Harry-kissing-Cho scene for example: Harry, Hermione and Ron
are sitting in the Gryffindor common room and discussing the event.
This is supposed to be a light scene, and we are supposed to feel warm
and happy for Harry. Grint and Radcliffe look relaxed and cheerful,
but Watson looks almost mortified - as if she is going to break into
tears or something any moment. Hermione has that lovely line in this
scene: &quot;just because you have the emotional range of a teaspoon ...&quot;
directed at Ron, and when Watson delivers that line, it comes out all
wrong. I think Watson has become a distinct liability in the series,
and I wouldn't mind too much if she got replaced in HBP. HBP is the
one book where the character of Hermione has to show some range -
jealousy at Ron, a little streak of meanness, a mature sisterliness
toward Ginny and Harry, and also embarrassment at the end when she
realizes that Harry was right all along about Malfoy being upto
something. I just don't think Emma Watson is going to be able to
portray all of that in the movie - she seems to have the &quot;emotional
range of a teaspoon&quot; as Hermione in the series.

-Cheers,

TD
